:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://indyvanguard.org/?p=1459";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:554:"I have been involved in LGBT advocacy since 2005.  As a PFLAG member, I joined with a coalition formed to pass a Human Rights Ordinance in Marion County.  Following that, I attended rallies and hearings about a proposed state constitutional ban of same-sex marriage here in Indiana.  I carried signs, I testified, I gave speeches.  For a while we were &#8230; <a href="http://indyvanguard.org/do-support-an-indiana-constitutional-amendment-banning-same-sex-marriage-if-not-please-read-this/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Annette Gross";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3769:"<div class="pf-content"><p>I have been involved in LGBT advocacy since 2005.  As a PFLAG member, I joined with a coalition formed to pass a Human Rights Ordinance in Marion County.  Following that, I attended rallies and hearings about a proposed state constitutional ban of same-sex marriage here in Indiana.  I carried signs, I testified, I gave speeches.  For a while we were able to hold that threat at bay.  Eventually, however, we were faced with the reality that more than quite a few Indiana legislators want to have this constitutional ban locked into the State Constitution.</p>
<p>At the end of June, when DOMA and Prop 8 were repealed, our own governor Mike Pence stated his sorrow over these repeals, and he reiterated that, in his view, marriage should be reserved for one man and one woman.  He stated, &#8220;Now that the Supreme Court has had its say on the federal government’s role in defining marriage, the people of Indiana should have their say about how marriage is understood and defined in our state&#8230;.  I look forward to supporting efforts by members of the Indiana General Assembly to place a constitutional amendment on the ballot for voter consideration next year.&#8221;</p>
<p>This caused a firestorm on Facebook and other social media sites.  Many people got angry with the governor for his statements.  A lot of talk was generated about HJR-6 and what should be done and how it should be done, etc.  Everyone seemed to have their own ideas.</p>
<p>Well, we are now at the brink.  The campaign to repeal HJR-6 is going to kick off within the next few weeks.  Led by Indiana Equality Action and other allied organizations, a campaign to mobilize thousands of people will be underway.  There will be phone banking, canvassing, and letter-writing taking place all throughout Indiana.</p>
<p>We already have a list of people who have volunteered to take part in these activities.  But that list is very small compared to what we need.  I recently read that the campaign in Minnesota mobilized 50,000 people to make phone calls.  That is what it&#8217;s going to take here in Indiana to do the work that needs to be done.</p>
<p>I am asking you to make the commitment NOW to join with us to repeal HJR-6.  It&#8217;s one thing to discuss it on Facebook, but we need real live bodies to do the necessary and important work.  Please volunteer to make calls and write letters.  Send me your name, e-mail address and phone number, and you will be put on the list.  As soon as these actions begin to take place, you will be contacted.  In addition, please share this request with your friends, family, co-workers, neighbors&#8211;and those in any organization you belong to.</p>
<p>This bill is intended to prevent all LGBT Hoosiers from being able to get legally married.  And the second sentence—a very muddy one—would prevent any relationship &#8220;similar to marriage&#8221; from also becoming legal.  Remember­­, we are not fighting for same-sex marriage rights in Indiana right now, we are working to stop a ban of same-sex marriage from getting into our state constitution.</p>
<p>So, please, contact me at <b>annette.gross@indianafreedom.org</b>.  I cannot stress how important it is that as many people as possible throughout the state join with us to fight this discriminatory amendment.  It will take a lot of work and a lot of people-power, but it can be done!  Thank you!!!!</p>
