		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:65:"Henrietta Lacks’ Legacy: Immortal Cells and Noble Grandchildren";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:191:"http://indyvanguard.org/henrietta-lacks-legacy-immortal-cells-and-noble-grandchildren/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=henrietta-lacks-legacy-immortal-cells-and-noble-grandchildren";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:95:"http://indyvanguard.org/henrietta-lacks-legacy-immortal-cells-and-noble-grandchildren/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 12 Aug 2013 16:00:03 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Thoughts";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Medical Research";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Privacy Rights";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://indyvanguard.org/?p=1452";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:527:"Last Tuesday (August 6, 2013), marked a milestone for ethical medical research and privacy rights. I’ll come to that soon, but first—Henrietta Lacks? Who is she and why am I writing about he. Henrietta Lacks would have been remembered by family, friends, and neighbors, but she would not be written about had it not been for the circumstances that accompanied &#8230; <a href="http://indyvanguard.org/henrietta-lacks-legacy-immortal-cells-and-noble-grandchildren/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"Len Farber";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7426:"<div class="pf-content"><p>Last Tuesday (August 6, 2013), marked a <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/08/science/after-decades-of-research-henrietta-lacks-family-is-asked-for-consent.html?pagewanted=all&amp;_r=1&amp;" target="_blank">milestone</a> for ethical medical research and privacy rights. I’ll come to that soon, but first—Henrietta Lacks? Who is she and why am I writing about he.</p>
<p>Henrietta Lacks would have been remembered by family, friends, and neighbors, but she would not be written about had it not been for the circumstances that accompanied her disease and death. <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henrietta_Lacks" target="_blank">Henrietta Lacks</a> was a semi-literate, African-American woman from Clover, Virginia (born in Roanoke). She died from ovarian cancer in 1951 at the young age of 31 at Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore, Maryland. It was the closest hospital to her home in Baltimore County that would treat black patients.  When she was first treated at Johns Hopkins, less than a year before her death, biopsy samples were collected of both healthy and cancerous cells from her uterus. When Dr. George Otto Gey took those cells and grew them in his laboratory, he discovered something unique and revolutionary. Some of those cells kept growing and dividing, over and over—and NEVER stopped. He had discovered the first immortal human cell line, the HeLa cell. What this meant for biomedical research cannot be understated. Among other things, it meant that the experiments conducted this month and the experiments conducted next month could use what were essentially the exact same cells. Researchers in San Francisco, New York and London, Mumbai and Tokyo could all use the exact same cells. HeLa cells were used in the development of the Salk polio vaccine. They were used in research on Parkinson’s disease, AIDS, leukemia, influenza and countless other diseases. They were sent into space to study the effects of zero gravity on the cells.</p>
<p>To see the importance of what we are talking about, I did a quick search in the National Library of Medicine&#8217;s online database for the number of published articles using some different cell lines. The C4 rat glioma cell, a cell line popular for basic research that I used in my studies, listed 15,326 articles; the MCF-7 human breast cancer cell line listed 17,095; the list for HeLa cells was 76,057.</p>
<p>I, like all biology students, learned about HeLa cells early in my career, but I didn’t learn about Henrietta Lacks. They came from “Helen Lane”, we were told. Or maybe it was &#8220;Helene Lange&#8221;. It was a secret to protect the family of the woman, who died, or possibly survived. You see, Dr. Gey never got permission to use those cells and the family of Henrietta Lacks was never told.</p>
<p>I should note that nobody asked for permission to use biopsied tissue in those days. The term &#8220;informed consent&#8221; didn&#8217;t exist. Today, if you go in for surgery or any procedure where tissue samples are taken, you will sign a consent form. On most, if not all, of those forms, you give permission for the tissue (your cells) to be used for other purposes, even to develop commercial products, without compensation. Henrietta Lacks never signed such a form. It was only in 1973, when a scientist contacted Ms. Lacks&#8217; children to ask for blood samples to research, that the truth about Henrietta Lacks and HeLa cells was finally revealed. Even after that revelation, few people knew about Henrietta Lacks until the publication of <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Immortal-Life-Henrietta-Lacks/dp/1400052181/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1376234036&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=the+immortal+life+of+henrietta+lacks" target="_blank">The Immortal Life of Henrietta Lacks</a> by <a href="http://rebeccaskloot.com/" target="_blank">Rebecca Skloot</a> in 2010.</p>
<p>I also must mention that Dr. Gey never made money off of the cells or from any of his contributions to science. He was a scientist of the old school where getting to spend your life researching the answers to questions about the world was the reward, not creating a &#8216;start up.&#8217; It is unclear whether he received a doctorate. His <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Otto_Gey" target="_blank">Wikipedia page</a> doesn&#8217;t mention it, while he is referred to as &#8220;Dr.&#8221; on <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henrietta_Lacks" target="_blank">Henrietta Lacks&#8217; Wikipedia page</a>. George Gey&#8217;s Wikipedia page also reports that when he was diagnosed with pancreatic cancer he had wanted some of his cells to be taken for scientific research. The surgeon didn&#8217;t comply and he was &#8220;furious&#8221; when he woke up from surgery.</p>
<p>HeLa cells, probably the most researched cell line in existence, were also the first cell line to have its genome <a href="http://g3journal.org/content/early/2013/03/26/g3.113.005777" target="_blank">completely sequenced</a> by scientists at the European Molecular Biology Laboratory. As is considered proper for scientific research, the results were made publically available so that other scientists could benefit from the work. When Henrietta Lacks’ descendants learned about this, they feared what the release of that genetic information might mean to the family, them and their children. To their credit, the research team at EMBL agreed to withdraw the results from public availability.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, another study sponsored by the National Institutes of Health was due to be published in the highly prestigious journal, <span style="text-decoration: underline;">Nature</span>. This publication was stopped. NIH Director Dr. Francis S. Collins and Deputy Director for science, outreach and policy Kathy L. Hudson made three separate trips to Baltimore to meet with the family. If I deem the descendants of Henrietta Lacks to be praiseworthy, it is because of what they sought and what they didn’t. They did not seek compensation and they did not seek to stop scientific progress. They only wanted to protect the family’s privacy and the ensure recognition for Henrietta. The agreement they reached should be a model for how the right to privacy and the needs of the research community can coexist. The NIH is establishing a HeLa Genome Data Access working group that will determine which scientists will have access to the genetic data. Both the European and the American sequencing data will be stored at the NIH and will be subject to review by this working group. Significantly, two of Henrietta’s descendants will sit on the board that makes these decisions.</p>
<p>The real legacy of Henrietta Lacks: cells that will live forever and enhance scientific research, and descendants that sought to ensure that the science continues while protecting the right to privacy of medical information. Of the two, we should be most thankful for the latter. I know I am.</p>
<p><b>Note</b>: Part of the proceeds from Rebecca Skloot&#8217;s book went to fund <a href="http://henriettalacksfoundation.org/" target="_blank">The Henrietta Lacks Foundation</a>. You can read an excerpt of the book at <a href="http://www.oprah.com/world/Excerpt-From-The-Immortal-Life-of-Henrietta-Lacks_1" target="_blank">Oprah Winfrey&#8217;s site</a>. Ms. Winfrey is in the process of turning the book into an HBO movie.</p>
