 not be subsidizing activity that my church considers immoral.” “Nobody is trying to ban birth control, but I don’t see why I should have to &#8230; <a href="http://indyvanguard.org/contraception-is-a-public-health-matter-not-a-political-volleyball/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"Mary Strinka";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2989:"<div class="pf-content"><p>Here are some examples of frequently encountered comments regarding contraception and insurance coverage:</p>
<blockquote><p> “If you want to use birth control, pay for it yourself.  It only costs $9 a month at Walmart.”</p>
<p>“The government should not be subsidizing activity that my church considers immoral.”</p>
<p>“Nobody is trying to ban birth control, but I don’t see why I should have to buy insurance that includes that benefit if I don’t use it.”</p></blockquote>
<p>Let me provide some counter-comments to the same topic:</p>
<p>Unintended pregnancy is a public health issue that affects all of society, not just a particular woman and her children.  Unintended pregnancies are more likely than planned pregnancies to have poor outcomes, like prematurity and low birth weight.  These problems impose health and financial burdens on individual families, and society as a whole.</p>
<p>Women who space their pregnancies by using contraception are more likely to have healthy children, and protect their own long-term health as well by conserving their calcium, iron, and other reserves.</p>
<p>In July 2011, the Institute of Medicine <a href="http://www.iom.edu/~/media/Files/Report%20Files/2011/Clinical-Preventive-Services-for-Women-Closing-the-Gaps/Preventive%20Services%20Women%202011%20Report%20Brief.pdf">issued a report</a>, <i>Clinical Preventive Services for Women: Closing the Gaps </i>, recommending that preventive care should include the full range of Food and Drug Administration-approved contraceptive meth­ods, sterilization procedures, and patient education and counseling for all women with reproductive capacity (along with seven  other specific recommendations which have not been so politically controversial).</p>
<p>Unintended pregnancy has additional social costs, as well as health consequences.  Unintended pregnancy can interrupt educational goals—temporarily or permanently—resulting in lower lifetime achievement and earnings.  Unintended pregnancies can disrupt marriages and relationships, resulting in both emotional pain and financial hardship.  These effects fall not only on the most recent child, but can also have negative consequences for any children already in the family.</p>
<p>While most women can access some form of contraception at their own expense, the fact is that some of the most effective forms of contraception have high up-front costs.  Thus, many women are currently using a less effective, or less appropriate, form of contraception than what they might choose when all forms are fully covered by insurance.</p>
<p>In short, the societal goals of a healthy population and stable families are best served when childbearing is intentional, not accidental.  Contraception should be available with no copay for all women (and men!) for the same reason that childhood immunizations are covered:  because the benefits to public health far outweigh the costs.</p>
</div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:96:"http://indyvanguard.org/contraception-is-a-public-health-matter-not-a-political-volleyball/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:48:"
		
		
		
		
		
				
		
		

		
		
				
			
		
