insurance exchange, new health information technologies, and the role of certified nurse anesthetists. But the first order of business, and what seemed like the longest discussion, was on the issue &#8230; <a href="http://indyvanguard.org/hoosier-civics-lesson-healthcare-is-a-privilege-reserved-for-the-chosen-few/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:17:"Concerned Citizen";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2329:"<div class="pf-content"><p>Last week, I spent a very long day listening to the summer meeting of the Health Finance Committee.  There were several important issues that were discussed, including the new health insurance exchange, new health information technologies, and the role of certified nurse anesthetists.</p>
<p>But the first order of business, and what seemed like the longest discussion, was on the issue of consumer fraud of Medicaid.  During the last legislative session, FSSA was asked how they monitor this kind of fraud, and because they could not answer the question well, they were told to have a report ready for this meeting.</p>
<p>To clarify, consumer fraud of Medicaid means one recipient defrauds the system.  An example given was a woman who had moved back into her husband’s house with her children, without informing her caseworker.  For this, she was jailed, and the state is attempting to recover $43,000 in health care expenses from her.  FSSA estimates the rate of consumer fraud of Medicaid to be 0.02%.  This means that of the more than 1 million Hoosiers who are on Medicaid, perhaps 250 of them have done something fraudulent in order to obtain healthcare.  I can’t tell you about provider fraud (such as home health care companies, providers, etc.) which accounts for many millions of dollars in fraudulent claims, because our legislators are apparently not interested in fraud perpetrated by businesses—just those individual Hoosiers who do things in order to get healthcare.</p>
<p>As the meeting went on, the angry diatribes on the part of the mostly white, male Republicans about cheating Hoosiers morphed into an attack on reduced and free lunches (let’s starve the children!).  One of them even admitted that to prove a point, when he registered his children for school he said his kids needed reduced price lunches, and nobody checked up on him!  And then, it morphed to reduced rental for text books, because the schools encourage both of these frauds so that they can get more money from the state to educate our children.</p>
<p>So what I learned about Hoosier civic values:  Access to healthcare is a privilege, and a healthy, well-fed, well-educated populace has no benefit to all Hoosiers, just to the selfish few who can afford access to these things.</p>
