;s:581:"As conversations swirl around the recent comments made by Pope Francis on his flight back from Brazil, I cannot help but be drawn in by the topic—after all, once a Catholic, always a Catholic…recovering….thanks Kate Clinton, for defining this. It was a welcome bone thrown to the gay community and his timing could not have been any better given the &#8230; <a href="http://indyvanguard.org/the-politics-of-religion-and-the-conscience-of-the-heart-how-important-were-the-popes-recent-comments-to-the-lgbt-community/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Regina Pilotte";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3262:"<div class="pf-content"><p>As conversations swirl around the recent comments made by Pope Francis on his flight back from Brazil, I cannot help but be drawn in by the topic—after all, once a Catholic, always a Catholic…recovering….thanks <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kate_Clinton" target="_blank">Kate Clinton</a>, for defining this.</p>
<p>It was a welcome bone thrown to the gay community and his timing could not have been any better given the marriage issue facing our community, but were his statements about his not wanting to judge gay priests aimed at soothing the wounds of the gay community?</p>
<p>Pastors and clergy have long understood the balancing act of touching the conscience without alienating the congregation, and the fact that gays and lesbians were not predominant in most religious communities has made speaking on the topic of homosexuality low-risk—until recently.  Increased visibility of the gay and lesbian community has pulled back the cloak that has covered a small but strong segment of the religious community and allowed friends and family to begin dialogue on the issue.  The issue that was once uniting in its unfamiliar, ‘freak-show’ way is now divisive as families and allies of gay and lesbian Catholics are speaking out.</p>
<p>While Catholic teaching is “Universal” by definition, the reality is that acceptance varies greatly depending on the congregation.  Perhaps some priests have a clearer understanding of the value of religious communities for all people, the value of all humans and choose to foster “inclusive” Catholic communities.  This is in spite of the fact that inclusion and acceptance is clearly not been the position of the Catholic Church.  In fact, the church allowed the gay community to become a convenient target when the reputation of the church had been stained by the inappropriate and illegal acts of priests.  The blurring of issues worked for awhile.</p>
<p>The Catholic community has been challenged by church doctrine that is conflicting and confusing on both an intellectual and emotional level when it comes to the gay community, and the current social climate for acceptance of same sex relationships has pushed Catholics who are attempting to reconcile with Church teachings on the issue.   The statements made by the Pope should not be mistaken as a change in doctrine, but as a politically wise attempt to unite a divided and conflicted church body and keep dollars in the coffers.</p>
<p>This is a baby step in the right direction for the Church, but really offers nothing for the gay and lesbian community and this is not likely to change.  It does, however, offer a grain of compassion for Catholics who are internally conflicted by this issue.  For too long, members of the church have been stuck in the smash between the politics of religion and the conscience of heart.  The Catholic Church, as well as other religious communities, can no longer afford to use the gay and lesbian community as the emotional diversion for those members who are unable to face their own ‘sin.’</p>
<p>The target has shifted and it is time for religious communities to acknowledge the four fingers that are pointing back at them as they judge.</p>
