:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"Erin Polley";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3376:"<div class="pf-content"><p>A year ago today I wrote a post titled, <a href="http://indyvanguard.org/why-i-breastfeed/" target="_blank">&#8220;Why I Breastfeed&#8221;</a> when my little one was just ten weeks old. Today he is 14 months and I am happy to report, we are still breastfeeding.</p>
<p>I&#8217;m still breastfeeding for all the reasons I started in the first place—for the health of my baby and myself, for the comfort and nourishment that I can provide him and because it just feels right for us. As he grows bigger and gains more independence each day, it&#8217;s a wonderful privilege to be able to connect with my child in this way and know that I am still able to help his growing body.</p>
<p>Unfortunately, breastfeeding a toddler is less socially acceptable than nursing a young baby. After his 1st birthday, the questions from friends and family started rolling in about our nursing relationship: &#8220;Have you weaned that baby yet?&#8221; and &#8220;How much longer will you be doing THAT?&#8221;</p>
<p>The truth of the matter is, I can&#8217;t say when I will stop breastfeeding. Just like I couldn&#8217;t predict the day my baby would take his first steps or say his first words, I can&#8217;t predict the day when he will decide he&#8217;s all done with his mama&#8217;s milk. I&#8217;m ok with that, my partner is ok with that and I&#8217;m sure my son is ok with that.</p>
<p>I have learned along the way, that there are still so many health benefits for breastfeeding into the toddler years. As my toddler grows more independent and is around other children more, the antibodies in my breast milk will protect his immune system and keep him healthy. My milk provides 75% of his Vitamin A requirements, 43% of his needed protein and 36% of his calcium requirements. While he continues to explore and experiment with new foods every day, it is a comfort to know that we don&#8217;t have to worry about him getting enough calories from food and that he can learn to enjoy food at his own pace.</p>
<p>I still breastfeed because I know that one day I will be sad that my baby is a baby no longer. It is those moments when my busy baby comes to me, shows the sign for &#8220;milk&#8221; and smiles hugely at me when he&#8217;s satisfied that I will treasure forever.</p>
<p><b><i>Erin Polley is a community organizer, peace activist, breastfeeding advocate and mother to Jack. Email her at </i></b><a href="mailto:erinpolley@gmail.com" target="_blank"><b><i>erinpolley@gmail.com</i></b></a><b><i>.</i></b></p>
<p><i>August 1-7 is World Breastfeeding Week and Governor Mike Pence has recognized this week as Indiana Breastfeeding Week. A proclamation will be read Saturday, Aug 3 at 10:30am by Joan Duwve, M.D., Chief Medical Officer at the Indiana State Department of Health as a part of the Big Latch On, sponsored by Indy Breastfeeding Moms, a chapter of Breastfeeding USA. For more information and to register, visit </i><a href="http://www.biglatchon.org/locations/indy-breastfeeding-moms-big-latch-on" target="_blank"><i>http://www.biglatchon.org/locations/indy-breastfeeding-moms-big-latch-on</i></a><i>.</i></p>
<p><i>For more information on breastfeeding or to see a copy of the Breastfeeding Week proclamation, visit </i><a href="http://www.statehealth.in.gov/" target="_blank"><i>www.StateHealth.in.gov</i></a><i>.</i></p>
