antly—it must confine itself to a few points and repeat them over and over.”  Joseph Goebbels The Pence Administration’s refusal to expand Medicaid under the Affordable Care Act (ACA) has already had a devastating impact upon Hoosiers. According to a February 2013 policy &#8230; <a href="http://indyvanguard.org/the-pence-administrations-despicable-lies-about-obamacare/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"Bill Groth";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4772:"<div class="pf-content"><blockquote><p>“The most brilliant propagandist technique will yield no success unless one fundamental principle is borne in mind constantly—it must confine itself to a few points and repeat them over and over.”  Joseph Goebbels</p></blockquote>
<p>The Pence Administration’s refusal to expand Medicaid under the Affordable Care Act (ACA) has already had a devastating impact upon Hoosiers. According to a February <a href="https://www.statereforum.org/sites/default/files/iha_unmc_indiana_medicaid_expansion_report.pdf" target="_blank">2013 policy brief</a> developed with the support of the Indiana Hospital Association, Indiana’s opposition to Medicaid expansion will leave more than 400,000 Hoosiers without health insurance. The estimated cost of expanding Medicaid to provide insurance to those 400,000 Hoosiers is a half a billion dollars, while the estimated revenue that would come to the State from the federal government by 2020 and which will now be forfeited is more than 20 times that amount ($10.45 billion).</p>
<p>Republicans in Congress have frequently claimed that the ACA will cause insurance costs for average Americans to skyrocket.  Recently a spokesman for the Pence Administration, its Department of Insurance chief deputy commissioner Logan Patrick Harrison, misleadingly announced that Hoosiers will see a huge increase in insurance premiums under the ACA. That claim has since been thoroughly debunked by <a href="http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2013/07/28/4196466/health-care-battle-fraught-with.html" target="_blank">independent observers</a>, who say Pence’s numbers were “an incredible simplification of an incredibly complex topic.”</p>
<p>Who is Logan Patrick Harrison?  It turns out he’s a 2007 graduate of IU Indianapolis Law School who was recruited by Mitch Daniels to work with Tony Bennett on educational policies. In 2010 Harrison published a book about his educational reform ideas, “Straight Ahead, As Usual: Education Reforms Put Simply,” a book Harrison describes as “highly critical of the current education model” and in which he urges the adoption of private school vouchers and praises Daniels and Bennett as exemplars of public education “reform.”</p>
<p>What is not clear is how Harrison became an alleged expert in the field of <i>public</i> education, given that he is a product of parochial elementary and high schools in Indianapolis and did not attend any public school until entering college.</p>
<p>What is even less certain is how, apart from serving as the mouthpiece of the Pence Administration, Harrison now qualifies as an expert in assessing the ACA’s impact upon the insurance premiums Hoosiers pay.</p>
<p>Hoosiers should be alarmed that the Pence Administration would allow a deeply partisan lawyer with no discernible expertise in health care policy to serve as a spokesperson regarding that issue.  And they should be incensed that he would use misleading numbers that are deliberately designed to inflate the ACA’s actual costs and to ignore the substantial savings and benefits the vast majority of Hoosiers will realize after the ACA is fully implemented.  After all, at his inauguration Pence swore an oath to faithfully carry out the law, and Obamacare is now the law of the land.</p>
<p>Gov. Pence knows (but won’t tell you) that after years of his political party publicly tearing it down, challenging it in court, and holding some 40 futile votes to repeal it, the ACA is likely to lower rather than raise health insurance premiums for most Hoosiers and expand health insurance coverage to many Hoosiers currently without health insurance, and even more if and when Pence finally agrees to Medicaid expansion.  But Pence, like so many of his fellow Republicans, apparently still believes he must do everything in his power to sabotage the ACA before it takes full effect, which includes lying to and misleading his constituents in order to weaken Its public support.</p>
<p>If the ACA is allowed to fulfill its promise to expand health insurance coverage to the uninsured, bring down health care costs, create jobs and improve the economy, Republican politicians who have tied their political fortunes to defeating Obamacare will be thoroughly discredited and will suffer the political consequences.  But political consequences aside, there is still no reason for Gov. Pence and his spokesman to make false and misleading statements about Obamacare which, despite Republicans’ best efforts to kill it, is now the law of the land and if given the opportunity can and will provide a better quality of life to thousands of Hoosiers who are either too sick or too poor to get the health coverage they need and deserve.</p>
