a month old. This isn’t the &#8230; <a href="http://indyvanguard.org/to-err-is-human-be-it-government-or-business-someone-should-have-planned-better/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"Len Farber";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3054:"<div class="pf-content"><p>Here is a day&#8217;s worth of some lighter thoughts.</p>
<p>On my way to work yesterday, I noticed the right lane blocked at College and Westfield—again. Looking at what was going on while waiting for the light to change, I noticed a man with a jackhammer breaking up the sidewalk—the newly poured sidewalk, less than a month old. This isn’t the first time I’ve seen newly poured sidewalks or newly paved streets being ripped up and it probably won’t be the last. You just think that someone should have planned better.</p>
<p>Then at work today, it was a déjà vu moment. In the middle of the code I was changing was a ‘date function’—actually two of them that used dates to determine ages. The first was the Y2K fix put into the code in 1999 (remember the Y2K scare?) and the second—a fix for the Y2K fix completed in 2001. You see, although everyone knew it was coming, both the private sector and the public sector waited until the last minute to fix this issue. Therefore many of the fixes were “quick and dirty”, temporary fixes that bought 5, 10 or 20 years. Having taken a deep breath, more rational, permanent fixes were made. Again, you just think that someone should have planned better.</p>
<p>On my lunch break, there was yet <a href="http://usnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/07/25/19680812-watchdog-sharply-critical-of-afghan-justice-training-program?lite" target="_blank">another news report</a> on the lack of oversight in a privatized government program, this one in Afghanistan. As I reflected on this and the notion that the private sector is always more ‘efficient’ than the public sector, I started to calculate the extreme wastefulness of the Y2K years, although it did get me into a new career in IT. Based on the billing rates that I know were prevalent then, and what I was told about the previous rates, I think the figure is in the tens of billions of dollars wasted nation-wide by the private sector alone.</p>
<p>On my return home, I continued a small project I have going, converting my VHS tapes to DVD. Some of these are home recordings, but most are movies I bought in the ‘excess inventory’ bins in various video rental stores. If you remember, Hollywood hated the idea of the VCR and wanted them to be banned by the government (they were more successful controlling DVD players). Hollywood failed and a booming business ensued. It allowed many ‘Mom &amp; Pop’ video stores to thrive (before Blockbuster put most of them under) and let Hollywood make a lot of money off of box office flops and some ‘direct to video&#8217; movies that never saw the inside of a theater. Fortunately, Hollywood didn’t plan better and a multi-billion dollar industry was born. While DVDs, often with “extra features”, have displaced video cassettes, this part of the industry really began because Hollywood’s idea of  &#8217;protecting&#8217; their property lost out. In this case, we can’t say somebody planned better, but somebody did have a better plan.</p>
